          "body": "The chapter opens with a startling inversion of the complaint of Isaiah 64. The people prayed as if God had withdrawn; God answers that He has been the one seeking. 'I permitted Myself to be sought by those who did not ask for Me; I permitted Myself to be found by those who did not seek Me' (65:1) — the divine initiative is unrequested, which is precisely its grace. Paul quotes this verse in Romans 10:20-21 and applies 65:1 to the Gentiles and 65:2 to Israel, reading the chapter as a prophecy of the church-age reversal in which Gentile response embarrasses Israelite refusal. The posture described in 65:2 — 'I have spread out My hands all day long' — is one of the Old Testament's most tender images of divine longing. God does not describe Himself as waiting behind closed doors; He is the host standing at the gate, arms extended, all day long. The tragedy of vv. 3-7 is that such arms are met with provocation rather than return."
