          "title": "The new wine in the cluster — grace that discriminates (65:8-16)",
          "body": "The chapter's turn at verse 8 is one of Isaiah's most carefully constructed images. A vineyard owner finds a cluster of grapes in what was written off as a dead vine — 'do not destroy it, for there is benefit in it.' God will act the same way: the nation as a whole has earned destruction, but within it are servants, chosen ones, offspring of Jacob, heirs of Judah (65:9) — a remnant that is not merely numerically smaller but qualitatively different. This is election embedded in judgment, grace operating within the bounds of wrath. For this remnant, the very geography of Israel's shame will be reversed: the valley of Achor, where Achan's sin fractured the conquest (Joshua 7), becomes a resting place for herds (65:10). The adversative 'but' of v. 11 is sharp: against the servants who seek God, those who set tables for Fortune and Destiny (*Gad* and *Meni* — Semitic astral deities of luck and fate) have chosen their master, and that master will deliver them to the sword. The four antithetical couplets of vv. 13-14 — eat/hungry, drink/thirsty, rejoice/ashamed, shout joyfully/wail with broken spirit — are the most concentrated expression of two-ways theology in Isaiah. Verse 15 completes the differentiation: the rebels leave their name as a curse; the servants receive another name. The promise of a new name previews the new-covenant identity of Isaiah 62:2 and Revelation 2:17."
