        "title": "The seeking God and the non-seeking people — grace preceding response",
        "range": "65:1-2",
        "excerpt": "I permitted Myself to be sought by those who did not ask for Me; I permitted Myself to be found by those who did not seek Me. I said, 'Here am I, here am I,' to a nation which did not call on My name.",
        "body": "The opening verses are the theological foundation for everything that follows, and they reverse the expected direction of the chapter's argument. Isaiah 64 ended with Israel's corporate lament — the people crying out as if God had left the stage. God's first word in chapter 65 is not 'I have been silent' but 'I have been speaking, and no one has been asking.' The structure of vv. 1-2 is chiastic: God found by those who did not seek (v.1) stands against God spreading His hands to those who did not come (v.2). The seeking posture belongs to God, not the people.\n\nThe apostle Paul reads this passage with precision in Romans 10:20-21. He attributes verse 1 ('found by those who did not seek Me') to the Gentiles — those outside the covenant who nevertheless came to faith — and verse 2 ('I have spread out My hands to a disobedient and obstinate people') to Israel. This is not allegory; it is Paul reading the historical logic of Isaiah's own argument: that the covenant people's refusal of the seeking God opens the door for those outside the covenant to enter. The Gentile mission of Acts is the fulfillment of what Isaiah 65:1 anticipated.\n\nThe phrase 'Here am I, here am I' (*hen hinneni, hen hinneni*) is the same response language used by Isaiah himself at his call ('Here am I, send me,' 6:8) and by Abraham at the binding of Isaac (Genesis 22:1). God is using the language of the servant-response as His own speech — He is the one making Himself available, the one presenting Himself for commissioning. The pathos is extraordinary: the God of the universe advertising His own availability to a people who have not asked.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Darash* (65:1, 10) — to seek, inquire, consult; used specifically of seeking God through prayer and oracle. *Paras yad* (spread out hands, 65:2) — an idiom of appeal or supplication; a gesture of invitation, not threat. *Sarar* (obstinate, rebellious, 65:2) — literally 'one who turns away,' from the root meaning to be stubborn or refuse to be led."
