        "excerpt": "A people who continually provoke Me to My face, offering sacrifices in gardens and burning incense on bricks… who say, 'Keep to yourself, do not come near me, for I am holier than you!'",
        "body": "The catalog of offenses in vv. 3-5 is forensic — every item is a specific violation that God has documented in His written record (65:6). The sequence moves from external cultic crime to the internal spiritual condition that generates it. Garden sacrifices, brick altars, necromantic vigils, and pork consumption (vv. 3-4) are the behavioral evidence. But verse 5 names the heart behind the behavior: 'I am holier than you.' This is the chapter's deepest indictment. These are not people who have abandoned religion — they are highly religious people who have substituted self-constructed holiness for God-defined holiness, and who use their religiosity to create distance from others rather than access to God.\n\nThe specific practices referenced identify this as classic syncretism. Garden worship and burning incense on bricks mirror Canaanite and Mesopotamian fertility cult practice. The grave-sitting and nocturnal secret-place gathering (65:4) describe *necromancy* — consulting the dead, forbidden in Leviticus 19:31 and Deuteronomy 18:10-12. Pork consumption is the most conspicuous dietary violation possible, the Mosaic food code's clearest marker of covenant identity (Leviticus 11:7). These people are not ignorant; they are deliberately crossing every line that distinguishes Israel from the nations. The 'broth of unclean meat in their pots' (65:4) is a detail of cultural contempt — cooking the forbidden food openly, at home.\n\nGod's description of the self-righteous in v. 5 — 'smoke in My nostrils, a fire that burns all the day' — is the inverse of the incense imagery in Numbers 16:46-48, where incense offered faithfully 'makes atonement.' Here the self-prescribed holiness does the opposite: it inflames. John Calvin notes on this verse that there is no form of sin more offensive to God than the pride that dresses itself in the garments of piety. The religious self-decorator who keeps others at arm's length under the banner of holiness is not merely proud — from God's perspective, they are combustion.\n\nThe repayment language of vv. 6-7 (*salem*, to pay in full, twice) is legal and precise. God has a ledger; it has not been wiped; the debt is compound, running across generations. The phrase 'into their bosom' echoes the covenant curse formulae of Deuteronomy 28 and the imprecatory language of Psalm 79:12 — retribution delivered directly and personally, not abstractly.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kaas* (provoke, 65:3) — to anger, vex, cause grief; used of Israel's perpetual provoking of God in Deuteronomy 32:21 and throughout Kings. *Piggul* (polluted broth, 65:4) — technically a term from Leviticus 7:18 for a sacrificial offering that has become ritually invalid; Isaiah uses it for forbidden food to maximize the covenant-violation register. *Salem* (repay, 65:6-7) — from the root *shalam*, the root of *shalom*; the divine repayment restores judicial balance."
